–1474","1375–1466":"1375–1466","1400–1498":"1400–1498","1360–Male":"1360–Afdød","1360–1414":"1360–1414","about 1380":"omkring 1380","Abt 1400":"omkring 1400","Cir 1474":"1474","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1414":"1414","1400":"1400","1466":"1466","1455":"1455","1498":"1498","1375":"1375","1474":"1474","Knodishall with Buxlow, Suffolk, England":"Knodishall with Buxlow, Suffolk, England","Knodishall, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Friston, Suffolk, England":"Friston, Suffolk, England"},"nl":{"about 1380–Cir 1474":"circa 1380–1474","1380–1474":"1380–1474","1375–1466":"1375–1466","1400–1498":"1400–1498","1360–Male":"1360–Overleden","1360–1414":"1360–1414","about 1380":"circa 1380","Abt 1400":"circa 1400","Cir 1474":"1474","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1414":"1414","1400":"1400","1466":"1466","1455":"1455","1498":"1498","1375":"1375","1474":"1474","Knodishall with Buxlow, Suffolk, England":"Knodishall with Buxlow, Suffolk, England","Knodishall, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Friston, Suffolk, England":"Friston, Suffolk, England"},"en":{"about 1380–Cir 1474":"about 1380–1474","1380–1474":"1380–1474","1375–1466":"1375–1466","1400–1498":"1400–1498","1360–Male":"1360–Deceased","1360–1414":"1360–1414","about 1380":"about 1380","Abt 1400":"about 1400","Cir 1474":"1474","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1414":"1414","1400":"1400","1466":"1466","1455":"1455","1498":"1498","1375":"1375","1474":"1474","Knodishall with Buxlow, Suffolk, England":"Knodishall with Buxlow, Suffolk, England","Knodishall, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Friston, Suffolk, England":"Friston, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Layston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Kent): possibly a variant of   Leeson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Leeson","meanings":["English (mainly Northamptonshire): metronymic from   Leece  1."]}]},{"name":"Jane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]},{"name":"Jaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."]},{"name":"Jain","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":75,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Jane Layston was born about 1380, in Knodishall with Buxlow, Suffolk, England, her father, John Layton, was 21 and her mother, Anne Maud Gerard, was 21. She married John Bokill II about 1400. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1474, in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 95."},"et":{"about 1380–Cir 1474":"umbes 1380–1474","1380–1474":"1380–1474","1375–1466":"1375–1466","1400–1498":"1400–1498","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","1360–1414":"1360–1414","about 1380":"umbes 1380","Abt 1400":"umbes 1400","Cir 1474":"1474","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1414":"1414","1400":"1400","1466":"1466","1455":"1455","1498":"1498","1375":"1375","1474":"1474","Knodishall with Buxlow, Suffolk, England":"Knodishall with Buxlow, Suffolk, England","Knodishall, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Friston, Suffolk, England":"Friston, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"about 1380–Cir 1474":"noin 1380–1474","1380–1474":"1380–1474","1375–1466":"1375–1466","1400–1498":"1400–1498","1360–Male":"1360–Kuollut","1360–1414":"1360–1414","about 1380":"noin 1380","Abt 1400":"noin 1400","Cir 1474":"1474","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1414":"1414","1400":"1400","1466":"1466","1455":"1455","1498":"1498","1375":"1375","1474":"1474","Knodishall with Buxlow, Suffolk, England":"Knodishall with Buxlow, Suffolk, England","Knodishall, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Friston, Suffolk, England":"Friston, Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"about 1380–Cir 1474":"environ 1380–1474","1380–1474":"1380–1474","1375–1466":"1375–1466","1400–1498":"1400–1498","1360–Male":"1360–Décédé","1360–1414":"1360–1414","about 1380":"environ 1380","Abt 1400":"environ 1400","Cir 1474":"1474","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"138